# Legal Aid Application Website - Comprehensive Build Prompt

---

## Project Overview

Build **myLegalAid** — a mobile-first, AMP-compatible national legal aid centralized intake website that connects individuals seeking legal assistance with appropriate legal aid providers using AI. The platform serves as both a public-facing accessibility, informational, and intake system for clients, as well as a secure provider management hub.

This is going to start out as a prototype with excellent UX but doesn't require all complex functionality to start with - it can be built out later. Images must be stellar. It must look very impressive and show what functionality will be available, even if some or much of the backend functionality is not built out at first.

This service/site will operate state-by-state, with Texas being the first state online.

The project aims to establish a centralized intake system for legal services in Texas, simplifying access for vulnerable individuals. It seeks to create one online portal and a toll-free phone access for intake across all practice areas, reducing barriers for clients seeking legal assistance. 

One intake system that can be accessed either through an online intake form or by phone.  Each provider will have a profile that includes a real-time "Capacity Meter." The Capacity Meter will be a tool that allows provider organizations to set parameters regarding their current priorities and capacity to take cases, specifically about which practice areas, geographic areas and level of service would be appropriate at any given time.

This will ensure that clients are sent to organizations where they are eligible for service, and who have the capacity to serve them, and that cases are triaged to get the appropriate level of service that they need. 

Provider organizations should realize huge savings as client intake activities will be done for them, allowing the provider to reallocate resources from intake to providing services. 

The intake system will employ guiding intake referral principles, essential scripts for proper intake across subject matter areas, continued feedback about the intake and referral process, and updates to the provider's Capacity Meter through the secure provider portal. Each provider can specify in their provider portal how they would like to receive referrals, by automated email, text message and/or industry standard webhook directly to their case management system. There will also be reporting capabilities available in the provider portal. Emergency cases or cases that require special attention could be routed to an attorney or designated person.

The intake system will can also assist clients with legal information and is expected to leverage the texaslawhelp.org website for this information.

Some of the most legal areas where vulnerable people need assistance include immigration, family law, domestic violence, housing and disability rights.

The intake system will be able to answer an unlimited number of calls, on the first ring, 24/7/365, in 32 languages. The system can be accessed either by calling a phone number or by using an online voice chat. With this AI intake system there is no need for retraining - an AI agent can be very quickly trained and it never forgets or needs retraining. There is never brain drain, call offs, bad days, etc.

When a legal aid service provider accesses their portal, one of the things they will be able to do is create service pods. For each service pod the provider can set a geographic area, legal area(s), referral capacity, whether it is information only, advice and counsel, brief services, or full representation, whether it is available only virtually or also in person, what language capacity is available, and what other accessibility can be provided for the client. Each provider can create any number of service pods for themself.  When a client completes an intake application and is deemed eligible for legal aid services, they will be referred to the provider if the client and their legal needs meet the provider's criteria specified in one of their service pods.

This system signifies a bold, forward-thinking approach to addressing systemic inequities and advancing access to justice. Through collaborative partnerships, innovative solutions, and a commitment to continuous improvement, the centralized intake project seeks to create a more inclusive and accessible legal aid ecosystem that serves the diverse needs of Texans across the state-removing the burden form the client the right resource, and shifting it to the providers. We believe that with innovative technology, applicants who we currently don't have capacity to serve can receive an answer quickly and get automated information and resources for self-help, thereby increasing the system's capacity and gain a sense of procedural justice for the client who would not otherwise be served.

This intake system can easily incorporate the intake requirements other programs and initiatives such as the Access and Visitation Hotline, Survivors of Sexual Assault (LASSA) program, Eviction Helpline programs, Veterans assistance programs, the South Central Pension Rights Project, Legal Hotline for Texans, Family hotline, Parenting Order Legal Line (POLL), MLP Program, and it can efficiently operate the intake portal for child welfare cases. The AI Agents can be quickly trained to assist in any subject matter area.

The system also provides an online intake application like what is found at [General Intake Online Form](https://www.tlsc.org/generalintake) and [Texas Family Help Link Online Intake Form](https://texaslawhelp.org/family-help-link).

This intake system is infinitely scalable, highly adaptible and ultimately sustainable. The system requires zero infrastructure additions or modifications by providers.

The anticipated impact of the Centralized Intake Project is multifaceted and holds the potential to significantly improve access to legal services for vulnerable Texans across the state. First, by streamlining the access to legal aid in Texas through a unified online portal and toll-free telephone system, the project aims to reduce barriers and enhance the ease of access for individuals seeking legal assistance. This streamlined approach will reduce or even eliminate the need for clients to navigate multiple intake systems, thereby saving time and reducing frustration. Additionally, the system addresses existing inefficiencies within the access to justice service delivery model by centralizing intake operations and optimizing resource allocation. Through the implementation of a provider service pods and the Capacity Meter tool, providers will be able to make real-time updates on their capacity to accept cases, ensuring that clients are efficiently matched with service providers who can meet their needs. 

Furthermore, the project aims to generate important and reliable data about client needs and the justice gap in Texas. By tracking and analyzing intake metrics, such as call volume, case acceptance rates, and reasons for rejection, the project will provide valuable insights into the demand for legal services and the ability of providers to respond. This data-driven approach will inform ongoing improvements to the intake and referral process, enabling stakeholders to make informed decisions and allocate resources more effectively. 

By leveraging technology, collaboration, and data-driven insights, this intake system streamlines the intake process, enhances service delivery, and ultimately, improve access to justice for vulnerable Texans. Through ongoing monitoring, evaluation, and process improvement, the AI technologies will continue to adapt and evolve, ensuring that it remains responsive to the needs of the community and delivers sustainable impact over the long term. 

We will ensure we are "closing the loop" on referrals by following up on any rejected referral or one that remains pending so that the volume of clients actually served should line up with the number of referrals made. We will also conduct ongoing client satisfaction surveys and partner feedback surveys to inform our QA processes and improve our services and systems. This will be done with automated AI agents that have unlimited capacity.

Legal Aid providers in Texas are committed to ensuring that clients are served in a trauma-informed, culturally competent, and efficient manner. Centralized intake furthers these goals by shifting the burden from the client to find the right resource to the legal aid community, reducing the re-trauma that clients often endure in our current system. 

This application is designed to be inclusive of and relevant to all legal aid providers in Texas, starting with the three LSC funded entities in Texas as well as Disability Rights Texas and the Texas Immigration Law Council, and Texas A&M University, moving to include all TAJF grantees, and finally opening up to any remaining legal aid providers in Texas.

Somewhere on the Legal Aid website should be mentions and links to [Qualifying for Legal Aid](https://texaslawhelp.org/qualifying-for-legal-aid), [Assisted Pro Se Services](https://texaslawhelp.org/assisted-pro-se-services), [Professional Use Only Legal Forms](https://texaslawhelp.org/warning-forms-for-professional-use)


---

## Core Mission & Purpose

Democratizes access to justice by:

- Making resources accessible — People seeking legal aid assistance have just one location to visit that provides them access to all legal aid statewide. The site, tools and resources are available and accessible 24/7 and in multiple languages.
- Simplifying intake — Using conversational AI to guide users through eligibility determination. Phones are answered 24/7 and in multiple languages.
- Continuity of service — Allowing users to track referrals and case status over time, follow-up, provide feedback, acccess additional resources.
- Provider empowerment — Giving legal aid organizations tools to define their ideal client profiles and manage the quantity and types of referrals they receive.
- Intelligent matching — Connecting clients with providers based on geography, legal issue, case status, and provider capacity, all based on the provider's profile settings.
- Resource management — Allows program administrators to track resource utilization, calls, legal aid needs, follow-ups, feedback, survey results, etc.

---

## Technical Requirements

### Mobile-First Architecture

- **90% mobile usage expected** — Every decision prioritizes mobile experience
- Touch-friendly interface elements (minimum 44px tap targets)
- Thumb-zone optimization for primary actions
- Swipe gestures for navigation where appropriate
- Progressive Web App (PWA) capabilities for offline access and home screen installation

### Framework & Styling

- **Tailwind CSS** for utility-first responsive design
- **Bootstrap 5** grid system and components where beneficial
- CSS custom properties for theming and consistency
- Mobile breakpoints: 320px, 375px, 414px, 768px, 1024px+

### AMP Compatibility

- Full AMP HTML compliance for all public-facing pages
- AMP components: amp-form, amp-bind, amp-list, amp-carousel, amp-accordion
- AMP-compatible conversational interface using amp-bind state management
- Valid AMP cache serving for Google Search integration
- Fallback progressive enhancement for non-AMP features

### SEO Implementation

- Semantic HTML5 structure
- Schema.org structured data (LegalService, Organization, FAQPage, HowTo)
- Open Graph and Twitter Card meta tags
- Canonical URLs and hreflang for future localization
- XML sitemap generation
- robots.txt configuration
- Core Web Vitals optimization (LCP < 2.5s, FID < 100ms, CLS < 0.1)

### Performance Targets

- First Contentful Paint: < 1.5s on 3G
- Time to Interactive: < 3.5s on 3G
- Total page weight: < 500KB initial load
- Lazy loading for below-fold content and images

### Header and Footer

- Consistent header and footer on all pages
- Header and footer to dynamically adjust based on display size
- Single code file for each header and for each page size across all pages
- Single code file for each footer and for each page size across all pages
- Logo (links to homepage)
- Sticky/fixed header on scroll
- Light/Dark mode toggle
- Language selector dropdown in header (see list above)
- Header and footer must be fully responsive and mobile-optimized.
- Hamburger menu for mobile.

### Languages
- Default: English
- Supported: 中文 (Chinese), English, Français (French), Deutsch (German), हिन्दी (Hindi), Русский (Russian), Español (Spanish), Tagalog (Tagalog), اُردُو (Urdu), Tiếng Việt (Vietnamese)
- Implement machine translation for missing ones (notify if incomplete)
- User language preference persists between pages.

---

## Design System & Aesthetics

### Design Philosophy
**"Accessible Authority"** — Trustworthy, approachable, and empowering. Users seeking legal help are often stressed and vulnerable. The design must feel:

- **Calm** — Reduce anxiety with clear hierarchy and breathing room
- **Trustworthy** — Professional enough to handle serious matters
- **Human** — Warm and supportive, not cold or bureaucratic
- **Clear** — Zero confusion about next steps

### Color Palette
```css
:root {
  /* Primary - Deep Trust Blue */
  --color-primary-900: #0D1B2A;
  --color-primary-700: #1B3A4B;
  --color-primary-500: #2D5A7B;
  --color-primary-300: #5B8FB9;
  --color-primary-100: #B8D4E8;
  
  /* Secondary - Warm Support Gold */
  --color-secondary-500: #D4A853;
  --color-secondary-300: #E8C97D;
  --color-secondary-100: #FBF3E0;
  
  /* Semantic Colors */
  --color-success: #2E7D32;
  --color-warning: #ED6C02;
  --color-error: #D32F2F;
  --color-info: #0288D1;
  
  /* Neutrals */
  --color-neutral-900: #1A1A2E;
  --color-neutral-700: #4A4A5C;
  --color-neutral-500: #6B6B7D;
  --color-neutral-300: #B8B8C4;
  --color-neutral-100: #F5F5F7;
  --color-white: #FFFFFF;
}
```

### Typography
- **Display/Headlines**: "Source Serif 4" — Elegant, readable, authoritative
- **Body/UI**: "IBM Plex Sans" — Humanist, accessible, excellent mobile rendering
- **Monospace (if needed)**: "IBM Plex Mono" — For case numbers, reference codes

### Typography Scale (Mobile-First)
```css
--text-xs: 0.75rem;    /* 12px - captions */
--text-sm: 0.875rem;   /* 14px - secondary text */
--text-base: 1rem;     /* 16px - body */
--text-lg: 1.125rem;   /* 18px - emphasized body */
--text-xl: 1.25rem;    /* 20px - section headers */
--text-2xl: 1.5rem;    /* 24px - page headers */
--text-3xl: 2rem;      /* 32px - hero headlines */
--text-4xl: 2.5rem;    /* 40px - display (desktop only) */
```

### Imagery Guidelines
- **Hero images**: Diverse, real people (not stock-looking) in professional but warm settings
- **Illustrations**: Custom line-art style showing legal concepts, pathways, connections
- **Icons**: Phosphor Icons or Heroicons — consistent stroke weight, filled for primary actions
- **Photography style**: Natural lighting, diverse representation, authentic moments of support and relief

### Motion & Interaction
- Subtle entrance animations (fade-up, 200-300ms, ease-out)
- Micro-interactions on buttons (scale 1.02 on hover, tactile feedback on mobile)
- Progress indicators with smooth transitions
- Loading states that feel responsive (skeleton screens, not spinners)

---

## Site Architecture & Pages

### Public Pages

#### 1. Homepage (`/`)
- **Hero Section**: Compelling headline, single clear CTA "Get Legal Help Now"
- **Trust Indicators**: Partner logos, statistics (X people helped, X providers)
- **How It Works**: 3-step visual process
- **FAQ Accordion**: Common questions (AMP-accordion)
- **Footer**: Resources, accessibility statement, privacy policy, terms of use

#### 2. Intake Flow (`/get-help`)
- **Conversational AI Interface**
  - Chat-style UI optimized for mobile
  - Progressive disclosure — one question at a time
  - Quick-reply buttons for common responses
  - Text input for open-ended questions
  - Real-time eligibility feedback
  - Save & resume capability (via secure link/code)

- **Intake Data Collected**:
  - Geographic location (county/state)
  - Legal issue category (family, housing, consumer, immigration, etc.)
  - Case urgency/status (pre-litigation, active case, emergency)
  - Income/household and household size to compute poverty level for eligibility
  - Preferred language
  - Contact information

- **Case Tracking**:
  - Automated follow-up
  - Facilitate success story approval and documentation

#### 3. My Cases (`/my-cases`)
- **Authentication**: Passwordless login (magic link or SMS code)
- **Dashboard**: List of referrals, status updates, provider contact info
- **Timeline view**: Track progress through referral to resolution
- **Document upload**: Secure file submission to providers
- **Messaging**: In-app communication with assigned provider

#### 4. About / Resources (`/about`, `/resources`)
- Mission and history
- Legal aid provider directory (searchable)
- Self-help resources and legal information
- Language and accessibility options

#### 5. Provider Portal Listing (`/provider-listing`)
- Value proposition for legal aid organizations
- Registration CTA
- Testimonials from partner organizations

### Secure Provider Portal (`/provider/*`)

#### Provider Dashboard (`/provider/dashboard`)
- Pending referrals requiring action
- Active case statistics
- Capacity overview
- Quick actions

#### Referral Management (`/provider/referrals`)
- Incoming referral queue
- Accept/decline with reason
- Client contact information
- Case notes and history
- Status updates

#### Profile & Criteria (`/provider/services-hub`)
- Organization information
- Service area (geographic boundaries via map interface)
- Legal issue categories served
- Eligibility criteria accepted
- Capacity meter (max cases per day and per week, pause referrals)
- Operating hours and contact methods

#### Profile & Criteria (`/provider/security`)
- Access controls
- Users
- User permissions

---

## Conversational AI Specification

### Personality & Tone
- **Name**: Consider a friendly name or keep generic ("Legal Aid Assistant")
- **Tone**: Warm, patient, encouraging, clear
- **Reading level**: 6th-8th grade (accessible to all literacy levels)
- **Empathy triggers**: Recognize stress indicators, offer reassurance

### Conversation Flow Architecture
```
START
  ├── Welcome & language preference
  ├── Geographic location
  │     └── Validate service area
  ├── Legal issue identification
  │     ├── Guided categories with examples
  │     └── "Tell me more" for complex situations
  ├── Urgency assessment
  │     └── Emergency routing if needed
  ├── Eligibility screening
  │     ├── Income questions
  │     └── Household composition
  ├── Summary & confirmation
  └── Referral generation
        ├── Match with providers
        ├── Present options (if multiple)
        └── Submit referral
```

### Error Handling
- Unclear inputs: "I want to make sure I understand. Could you tell me more about..."
- Out of scope: "I'm not able to help with [X], but here are some resources..."
- No matches: "I couldn't find a provider for your specific situation, but let me suggest..."

### Data Privacy in Chat
- No PII displayed after submission
- Session-based until account creation
- Clear data retention disclosures

---

## Accessibility Requirements (WCAG 2.1 AA+)

- Color contrast minimum 4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for large text and UI
- Full keyboard navigation
- Screen reader optimized (ARIA labels, live regions for chat)
- Focus indicators visible
- Reduced motion option (`prefers-reduced-motion`)
- Text resizable to 200% without loss
- Touch targets minimum 44x44px
- Captions for any video content
- Plain language throughout

---

## Security Considerations

### Public Intake
- Rate limiting on submissions
- CAPTCHA alternative (honeypot + timing)
- Input sanitization
- No PII in URLs or logs

### Authenticated Areas
- Passwordless authentication (magic links, SMS OTP)
- Session management with secure cookies
- Role-based access control (RBAC)
- Audit logging for all actions
- Data encryption at rest and in transit

### Provider Portal
- Multi-factor authentication option
- IP allowlisting option for organizations
- Session timeout (30 min inactivity)
- Secure file handling for documents

